08:45.680 --> 08:45.800
doing.

08:45.980 --> 08:50.300
Arthur thinks it's the first because he complains bitterly when people say it's his best because

08:50.300 --> 08:52.120
he likes to think that he's progressed since then.

08:52.140 --> 08:53.560
New Pole was his first published one.

08:53.560 --> 08:56.320
Maybe, but at any rate, one of his first.

08:56.780 --> 09:00.440
And which I think is a fine story and it's, it's not the invention in it.

09:00.480 --> 09:02.060
It's not the science in it.

09:02.060 --> 09:08.780
It's the feeling you have of a whole group of cultures meeting and interacting on each

09:08.780 --> 09:10.700
other in a way that's never happened in the world.

09:10.840 --> 09:10.960
Yes.

09:11.120 --> 09:13.280
Arthur was once accused and he hated it.

09:13.800 --> 09:17.580
And yet there's an element of truth in it, of having a very pedestrian imagination.

09:18.180 --> 09:19.940
I don't take that the way the writer meant it.

09:19.940 --> 09:23.600
Arthur does have a pedestrian imagination, which is a great asset to a writer.

09:23.760 --> 09:26.040
What he has is, he has an imagination.

09:26.440 --> 09:29.920
And we've mentioned things about his imagination and sometimes it's quite free-wheeling.

09:30.040 --> 09:34.580
But most of the time it is pedestrian in this sense that Arthur's imagination works step

09:34.580 --> 09:37.840
by step by step by step so that he details everything.

09:38.340 --> 09:42.920
He follows all the details except when he gets into a slightly mystical frame when he

09:42.920 --> 09:43.360
goes off.

09:43.620 --> 09:47.540
But his imagination and imaginary situations are detailed.

09:48.130 --> 09:49.780
You know how many legs the chair has.

09:50.300 --> 09:52.940
You know where the rungs are somehow in Arthur's stories.

09:53.900 --> 09:55.860
Pedestrian is not a word I would apply to Arthur's.

09:55.940 --> 09:57.640
I'm misusing the word deliberate.

09:57.700 --> 10:01.580
There is a word that I would apply to it that's almost equally pejorative.

10:01.740 --> 10:02.500
I think it's lucid.

10:02.940 --> 10:07.540
What impresses me most about Clark as a writer is that I understand what he's trying to communicate

10:07.540 --> 10:08.220
in every line.

10:08.220 --> 10:08.440
Yes.

10:08.640 --> 10:09.620
There's no obfuscation.

10:09.800 --> 10:12.740
There's no playing around with words just for the sake of the sound of them.

10:12.900 --> 10:16.160
Oh, what he is, he's very methodical in his thinking.

10:16.160 --> 10:17.180
Very methodically.

10:17.180 --> 10:18.080
He works everything out.

10:18.240 --> 10:23.040
And this is what the other writer, the critic called Pedestrian, which is really unfair

10:23.040 --> 10:24.280
in the usual meaning of the word.

10:24.540 --> 10:29.380
Fitting terms on Arthur, I would have used the word three dimensional.

10:30.120 --> 10:34.600
You remember in the fall of Moondust, the particular reality.

10:34.720 --> 10:34.800
It gets the fall of night.

10:35.100 --> 10:35.780
