10:35.860 --> 10:36.880
I guess the fall of night, yeah.

10:37.120 --> 10:37.540
That's right.

10:38.180 --> 10:44.780
But in the fall of Moondust, when the people are buried under this dust, the scene is particularly

10:44.780 --> 10:46.480
real because it's particularly solid.

10:46.880 --> 10:52.060
The world which is now narrowed down to the inside of this little sightseeing bus really

10:52.060 --> 10:56.280
has become a very hard world.

10:56.400 --> 10:57.040
You can touch it.

10:57.520 --> 10:58.940
Well, that's the trick that Arthur has.

10:59.080 --> 11:03.740
Arthur measures his future without ever losing sight of the romance of it because he still

11:03.740 --> 11:04.500
loves his futures.

11:05.020 --> 11:05.660
He measures.

11:06.160 --> 11:08.020
He knows just where everything is located.

11:08.280 --> 11:09.900
And it's a strong asset.

11:09.900 --> 11:15.680
This thoroughness, this methodical way with which he goes about making his imagination

11:15.680 --> 11:16.220
real.

11:16.560 --> 11:20.480
You'll notice, by the way, that science fiction does not get outmoded if it's good.

11:20.940 --> 11:26.380
The fact that the Moondust surface is not dusty, as some people thought before the first

11:26.380 --> 11:29.840
landing, does not make a fall of Moondust a bad story now.

11:30.080 --> 11:34.240
In the same way, the fact that we can go around the world in 80 minutes doesn't at least

