16:15.920 --> 16:19.740
For another eight years he didn't write anything because nobody happened to read that magazine,

16:20.080 --> 16:21.620
which had a circulation of four.

16:21.660 --> 16:23.240
Well, didn't you get into writing again, Fred?

16:23.400 --> 16:27.580
I did reprint that story in an anthology I did a couple years later, which I think is

16:27.580 --> 16:30.800
the first time he ever reached more than four people with one story.

16:31.380 --> 16:36.800
And he didn't write more, I think, not so much because he didn't get feedback, but

16:36.800 --> 16:41.760
because I don't think he was aware of the existence of magazines to publish the stories.

16:41.760 --> 16:48.180
I don't think Paul Weinbarger, which was his real name, actually read very much science

16:48.180 --> 16:52.680
fiction uniquely among the good writers of science fiction I know.

16:53.100 --> 16:58.980
And it wasn't until editors like Horace Gold and A Little Later Myself began getting after

16:58.980 --> 17:01.800
him and urging him to write that he began producing in volume.

17:02.180 --> 17:03.220
How old was he when he died?

17:03.540 --> 17:05.200
In his middle sixties.

17:05.860 --> 17:11.840
His whole science fiction writing career, except for two stories, occupied about five

17:11.840 --> 17:16.220
years from about 59 to 64, I think it was when he died.

17:17.720 --> 17:23.340
During which time he produced a body of work that has as large a coterie audience as most

17:23.340 --> 17:24.960
writers who were writing for 40 years.

17:25.860 --> 17:29.680
Yeah, well, a lot of that, not all of it, but a lot of it is in print now, fortunately.

17:29.680 --> 17:37.760
And for the first time, his novel, North Australia, Old North Australia, which is a planet not

17:37.760 --> 17:38.560
located on Earth.

17:39.040 --> 17:43.740
North Australia is available in complete form, and it was previously chopped up into pieces

17:43.740 --> 17:44.360
and butchered.

17:46.040 --> 17:48.940
So he's really reaching his maximum audience now.

17:49.180 --> 17:56.340
Kurt Weiner Smith under his real name, Paul Weinbarger, was a specialist in Eastern affairs

17:56.340 --> 17:57.500
for the State Department.

17:58.280 --> 18:03.200
He'd been born, I think, in China and lived there for a long time and spent a lot of time

18:03.200 --> 18:04.320
commuting back and forth.

18:04.760 --> 18:10.960
Last year when I was traveling in Eastern Europe for the State Department, I went to

18:10.960 --> 18:15.820
a particular city where the American ambassador was known to be hostile to all writers and

18:15.820 --> 18:17.700
to science fiction writers in particular.

18:18.360 --> 18:22.860
And when I was introduced to the ambassador, I expected he had a hard time, but it turned

18:22.860 --> 18:27.340
out that he had been a student of Weinbarger's and he mellowed immensely.

18:40.280 --> 18:43.040
Two questions were then posed to the panel.

18:43.620 --> 18:46.020
What book would you most like to be remembered for?

18:46.480 --> 18:49.480
And what book by a colleague do you wish you had written?

18:50.180 --> 18:51.020
Isaac Asimov.

18:51.470 --> 18:56.620
If I'm going to be remembered, it's probably going to be for the Foundation trilogy.

18:57.200 --> 19:02.080
But what I would like to be remembered for is the second part of the Gods themselves.

19:02.700 --> 19:07.860
Because I have frequently been told I don't write any sex and that I don't write any

19:08.400 --> 19:11.880
extraterrestrials and I wanted to show the world I could write about extraterrestrials

19:11.880 --> 19:13.940
and wanted to show them I could write about sex.

19:14.400 --> 19:20.560
So I wrote the second part of the Gods themselves which was completely and 100% about extraterrestrial

19:20.560 --> 19:20.840
sex.

19:21.780 --> 19:27.940
And it was the best extraterrestrials ever anyone ever wrote about and the best extraterrestrial

19:27.940 --> 19:29.560
sex anyone ever wrote about.

19:30.120 --> 19:35.120
And if I have to be asked what story by somebody else I would really like to have written,

19:35.680 --> 19:43.640
it would be Neutron Star by Larry Niven because I once wrote an article about tides and when

19:43.640 --> 19:46.820
I saw this story for which he won a Hugo, I said to myself-

19:46.820 --> 19:47.060
And the Nebula.

19:47.060 --> 19:52.060
And the Nebula, I said to myself my goodness I could have written that story because I

19:52.060 --> 19:56.860
had the entire background in my article and I said to Larry Niven you know I could have

19:56.860 --> 19:59.600
written that story because I had the entire background in the article.

19:59.800 --> 20:01.540
He said I know I read the article that's right.

20:03.580 --> 20:04.460
Frederick Poe.

20:04.620 --> 20:11.840
If I were to choose one story to be engraved on my tombstone, it would have to be a big

20:11.840 --> 20:13.900
tombstone because I'd like to choose three.

20:13.900 --> 20:19.300
There's a short story called Day Million which I wrote so easily and painlessly that I've

20:19.300 --> 20:25.040
always been desperate to recapture that flow of inspiration that came out so quickly and

20:25.040 --> 20:25.340
happily.

20:25.980 --> 20:31.260
There's a novel called The Gold at the Starbow's End and there's a novel not yet published

20:31.260 --> 20:35.640
called Gateway which I think is the best of them all but it's 100,000 words so I don't

20:35.640 --> 20:37.760
know how much of it you can engrave on a tombstone.

20:38.560 --> 20:42.480
As for what other people have written that I wish I had written, there's a lot of H.G.

20:42.480 --> 20:44.380
Wells that I admire immensely.

20:45.500 --> 20:54.600
Novels and short stories that show a sort of ability not just to write well or to write

20:54.600 --> 20:58.180
interestingly but to invent whole new areas of writing.

20:58.340 --> 21:03.640
The time machine is a major invention and I wish I could have written something like

21:03.640 --> 21:03.900
that.

21:04.200 --> 21:05.060
Lester Del Ray.

21:05.360 --> 21:08.620
I find myself in a peculiar position on the second part of this.

21:08.620 --> 21:13.400
As to what I wrote, I don't in the first place expect to be remembered.

21:13.920 --> 21:17.840
Oh, I suppose some of my stuff will be remembered by people who read it while they were very

21:17.840 --> 21:21.800
young until 50 years after I was dead but I really don't think.

21:22.560 --> 21:26.720
If I wanted to be remembered, I wouldn't have picked a somewhat transient feel like science

21:26.720 --> 21:32.280
fiction where your stories inevitably do get out of date sometimes and well your chances

21:32.280 --> 21:36.920
of being remembered by the critics are smaller, used to be smaller than elsewhere.

21:38.000 --> 21:42.500
I'm not writing for the ages, I'm writing for my own pleasure and for the readers of

21:42.500 --> 21:48.620
the day and if they are happy with my things and if I enjoy what I'm doing, sufficient

21:48.620 --> 21:50.900
under the day is the good thereof as well as the evil.

21:51.940 --> 21:57.860
I suppose if I had to pick one story, just one, to be remembered, I'd be torn between

21:57.860 --> 21:58.320
two.

21:58.860 --> 22:04.560
Helen Law in spite of the fact it was my second story and a story I wrote for Fred Pole and

22:04.560 --> 22:06.780
that was for I am a jealous people.

22:07.320 --> 22:15.240
As to somebody else's story I wish I'd written, one small short story by a man named Joseph

22:15.240 --> 22:20.200
Caleum which most people have forgotten called when the eagles gather perhaps.

22:20.940 --> 22:25.360
But generally, I don't feel that way about other writers' work, I'm glad they wrote it,

22:25.440 --> 22:26.400
I enjoy it thoroughly.

22:27.280 --> 22:31.540
I find enough of their individuality in it as a rule that I don't want to.

22:31.620 --> 22:32.040
There is.

22:32.040 --> 22:34.700
Do you remember the last line of that story Lester?

22:35.560 --> 22:40.140
Is that the one that ended about it as a...

22:40.140 --> 22:43.400
No, no, no, that was a McFarlane story you're thinking of.

22:43.580 --> 22:49.660
The story of another man's that I wish I could write has not been written yet.

22:49.920 --> 22:55.340
That consists of the last three books which Isaac Hassamnoff has not written to finish

22:55.340 --> 22:57.040
up his foundation series.

22:58.260 --> 23:00.120
Well, she gave me the right to write.

23:01.380 --> 23:03.020
For the record I never did.

23:03.280 --> 23:06.100
For the record it's in print and on tape that you did.

23:06.820 --> 23:09.660
Which he now, being an Indian giver, has taken back.

23:11.980 --> 23:12.860
It blot!

23:13.400 --> 23:14.580
It blots somebody else's.

23:15.580 --> 23:16.540
Gordon Dixon.

23:16.960 --> 23:20.540
This is a hard thing for me to answer, not because I have any doubt about the answer,

23:20.660 --> 23:22.120
but it's fitting the category.

23:22.700 --> 23:25.860
See, I have absolutely no doubt about what I want to be remembered for.

23:25.860 --> 23:26.680
It's the child's title.

23:27.180 --> 23:30.000
But I am going to have to do the whole Blinken thing to do it.

23:30.240 --> 23:35.260
Because only if I do it right will it turn out to be a structured piece of fiction in

23:35.260 --> 23:36.120
twelve parts.

23:36.900 --> 23:41.160
Running through the historical framework, the contemporary framework, and into the future

23:41.760 --> 23:42.560
fiction framework.

23:46.240 --> 23:51.940
And also of a type that I firmly believe and hope has not been done before that I have

23:51.940 --> 23:53.460
labeled the conscious thematic novel.

23:54.660 --> 23:59.220
So, it will take me fifteen more years to do it and at the end of that time, if I've

23:59.220 --> 24:01.780
done it right it will come out that way and I want to be remembered for it.

24:02.260 --> 24:07.980
As far as I've got a different type of problem in choosing a book that I wish I had written

24:07.980 --> 24:12.900
because I have to sort of grab it random between about a dozen books.

24:14.040 --> 24:17.460
I've already mentioned Arthur's childhoods end.

24:17.460 --> 24:23.820
I picked Paul's Brainwave and I pulled one of my famous blankouts, Jontting.

24:24.600 --> 24:25.180
Alfie Bester.

24:26.420 --> 24:30.160
Alfie's Tiger, Tiger, or Star's My Destination.

24:30.240 --> 24:31.960
Star's My Destination is what I'm thinking of.

24:32.460 --> 24:36.000
But I can go on and name, as I say, eight to ten more.

24:36.540 --> 24:39.700
What I want from each one of them is one particular thing.

24:40.100 --> 24:44.400
See, I'd like to take the ring out of the idols I, or nose here, and you know, steal

24:45.320 --> 24:49.560
the jewel from its gown someplace else, this type of thing.

24:49.820 --> 24:54.160
It's difficult really for anybody, for me at least, and I think for most writers, to

24:54.160 --> 24:57.980
say what story of someone else's he wishes he had written.

24:58.140 --> 25:01.720
There are a lot of stories that are inordinately successful and I wish I had had stories that

25:01.720 --> 25:05.080
successful, which have been one award that I haven't won and so on.

25:05.660 --> 25:12.160
But the only thing any writer has to sell is his own individual personal point of view.

25:12.160 --> 25:18.100
And there would be no way for me to have written Nightfall, or the Foundation series, or Hell in a Law,

25:18.300 --> 25:22.920
or any of the great stories that I've admired so much, because they weren't my stories.

25:23.000 --> 25:25.020
The only stories I know how to write are mine.

25:26.140 --> 25:27.880
Settle for that, Fred. They're pretty good.

25:28.400 --> 25:34.960
I think that is generally true. I think that when we say, I wish I had written that, we do always see one thing in it.

25:35.000 --> 25:38.580
That's near and dear to our heart and we wish we'd had the chance to write the story about that.

25:39.240 --> 25:41.740
Can I end by telling you a little anecdote?

25:42.680 --> 25:43.600
Can we stop you?

25:44.100 --> 25:44.780
No, you can.

25:45.760 --> 25:53.060
Fred Paul and I, Isaac Asimov and Ben Bolver and Gordie Dixon were the few attached ladies.

25:53.280 --> 26:00.780
We're sitting around a single table in Toronto at the World Science Fiction Convention there, a couple years, 73.

26:01.780 --> 26:04.680
Agonizing, he had meal, I remember it well.

26:04.680 --> 26:12.760
Yes, I won the Hugo from the novel and Fred won it for the short story and Ben won it for editorship.

26:13.140 --> 26:19.360
And there they were, a series of Hugo's at the table and we all turned, well at least I turned to Gordie Dixon.

26:19.540 --> 26:21.340
I said, Gordie, you're disgracing us.

26:22.460 --> 26:23.660
And I hung my head.

26:23.940 --> 26:24.740
Yes, you did.

26:40.660 --> 26:44.780
This has been the Valentine Science Fiction Hour.

